title: For Sale/Trade:  TT-33 Tokarev pistol 7.62 x25 - Unusual Hungarian variation
postcontent:
For sale is the Hungarian version of the famous TT-33 Tokarev pistol chambered in the powerful 7.62 x 25 caliber round. These Hungarian pistols were imported into the USA in far lesser quantities than the more common Chinese, Polish, and the more recent Yugo varieties. So it's seen far less and is more collectible than the more common varieties.

This particular pistol is in very good overall physical condition especially when you consider that it was an issue pistol that saw either military or police service. Mechanically it is in excellent shape with a  bright shiny bore and a reliable action. It retains the majority of it's original finish but does have the normal wear from being holster carried. It was manufactured in 1951 and is serial #1231. The numbers on the slide and frame match.

I researched the Hungarian variety of the TT-33 and discovered that they call it the M48. It was built almost identically to the Russian models, but it's distinguishing feature is the black plastic grips that have the Hungarian/Communist "hammer & wheat" seal embossed into them.

Pistol comes with an original (not reproduction) holster, two original magazines, original cleaning rod, & leather lanyard. Also included is a 70 round box of hot Polish ammo that is clean, shiny and sure to fire.

Price is $575.00

Transaction - FTF, cash (or trade) and you pick up. Must be a Florida resident and at least 21.

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  SKS Tactical: PRICE DROP!!!nicest I've seen on here; comes with 2 scopes plus++
postcontent:
Comes with 2 scopes: Chinese Norinco SKS:  Very impressive rifle in every way. Black tapcoT-6  6-position stock. Expands or contracts to fit any shooter.
Bayonet AND front foregrip installed, see pictures. You don't find that often, it's pretty great. Bayonet fits snugly into bayonet slot as it should when it's closed, and it clears the foregrip at all times.
All Numbers Match, excellent condition throughout. Cycles, fires and functions flawlessly. Selling to pay my bills and asking for a firm and very fair price.
You get the SKS rifle in the TAPCO stock.
2 TAPCO detachable 20 round magazines.
TANGO-DOWN brand, front foregrip installed.
SKS spike bayonet installed and fully functional with the foregrip in place.
Hi-Rise cheek rest that you can take off as you wish. It sets perfectly to line you up with the 4x32 scope. 
This rifle is tight as a drum and the action is like new. Whole thing looks and functions like new. Front and rear iron sites, (which are adjustable to 1100 yards/1000 meters [and the numbers are printed right on the rear site], can be seen perfectly, even with the scope installed. You can use the iron sites or the 4x32 sniper scope, it's your choice.
Two scopes come with the rifle, see pics. The 4x32 sniper scope, as seen in the pic. It sits atop a receiver cover that has 4 factory hold-down screws that keep this thing rigidly in place. It used to be that a receiver mounted scope "walked around" a bit and was a bad choice because the receiver cover would move slightly after multiple shots, but this 5th generation receiver cover from UTG with the set screws and retainer nuts is the real-deal and it is a rigid and excellent set up that will not move after you zero your scope. Rifle also has the shell deflector installed so the expelled shells don't hit your scope.
If you don't want to use the magnifying scope, loosen the nuts and pull the pin on the receiver cover and take off the whole 4x32 set-up...(((it's all bolted together, receiver cover, scope and mounts and shell deflector and comes off easily as one unit)))...then pop the original receiver cover on (which is included of course) and then install your projection red-dot scope, also included in this deal(as seen in the picture). This red-dot scope is of good quality and works great. If you don't know what a Red-Dot scope is, it is for QUICK shouldering and aiming of rifle. One dot, that's all.... no lining up the front and rear site. Turn the switch on, then appears on the screen- One red dot...put that dot on your target and pull the trigger. It works perfect and the technology, I don't really even understand.  But it's faster than open sites ever could be. I've got a red-dot on my shotgun too. 
The only thing that I don't have for this is a strap. But it has the strap mounts on the gun and is ready for you to install one if you want.
This is kind of my dream rifle, so-to-speak. It's just a gun, but it is pretty great. I am parting with it because God gave me enough sense to sell it when I can't pay my bills.
I'll throw in 20 rounds of non-corrosive Wolf ammo, so that you have a little ammo to start.   And I have about 700 rounds that I'll sell you:   50 cents a round- That's what I paid for it- and that's what I'll sell it for. As many as you want up till their gone. I don't need any ammo if the gun is gone obviously.  It's great:  Thanks.

title: For Sale:  AMMO CHEAP
postcontent:
Quick economics lesson for everyone selling ammo at 2-3x's retail. When ammo is finally available in large quantities (maybe 3 months if YOU are lucky) you will be out even more money. Right now, the ammo you have is "worth" at most 0.65 per round. You try and sell said ammo for $1.00 per round. If you got tricked into paying 0.85 per round, I understand your pain, most of us did the same. Here is the lesson. If you make your ammo prices reasonable now, you will make some of your money back. Losing money SUCKS, we get it. But, if you wait 3-5 months to sell your ammo back, and the retailers are selling ammo for 0.30 per round, you will lose even more. ARMSLIST was created to make both sides (buyer and seller) happy. If we wanted to be screwed we would all buy ammo at the range. Do EVERYONE a favor and start making DEALS, not killings. Some A-Holes at Super Dave's in Norman were trying to sell .223 for 1.25 per round and .22 for 100 per brick. The best part, a booth right across the way had it all for HALF THE PRICE.  Seriously, HALF THE PRICE. The prices made the over-priced table look like a group of spoiled kids on the playground showing off. Don't be "that" guy.

We've all been part of the problem before, but we are the only ones that can resolve the issue.

postcontent:
Won't bother talking about the various merits of the cz-52, if you're unfamiliar with them read up at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CZ_52.  It is a big hunk of indestructible steel, and beauty is in the eye of the beholder.  

This gun has matching serial numbers and no modifications done to it have changed the stock parts (all of which minus the crummy grips are included).  That said, if you're looking for a stock CZ-52 this isn't for you and you should be able to pick one up for $225-$300ish.

This one features extended mag floor plates (one installed, one yet to be installed), custom wood grips, after market firing pin, trigger job, western-style thumb slide release, standard leather holster, cleaning rod, two standard magazines.  7.62x25mm which will go through about anything, also doubles as a flame thrower and makes for a good club.  Fully functional.  You won't see too many that look like this.

Asking $500 sale/trade value and am pretty inflexible on that -- I've sunk at least that much money into it not including time over the years.  I'm in no particular rush to get rid of it, but I'm ready to move onto something else.  Happy to answer any pertinent questions, send additional photos etc.

title: For Sale:  1940's-era Velo Dog with folding trigger
postcontent: I found this in a box from my late father's estate. I know nothing about guns so this is new territory for me! My dad was in WWII so I am assuming that he brought this back with him from Europe. I have finally got a definite ID on the gun. It is a Velo Dog. It was introduced in 1894 in France as a gun to keep dogs away while riding bicycles. Although designed in France, it was mainly manufactured in Belgium. They were made in 22,25,and 32 cal. configurations, if I understand it correctly. It is a 5 shot revolver with a folding trigger. The action is still good and everything seems to work. It hasn't been restored, but it has been cleaned and oiled.  Some of the markings on it are "p8f", "6.35Br", "37", and "PVRC", with  a crown over the Rand a star over the C. There is another symbol over the P, but I can't make it out. That's about all I can tell you about this gun. I feel like it has a connection to WWII somehow, but I can't be sure. My dad talked about finding a gun on the ground when he was at the Battle of the Bulge, but I couldn't say for sure if this is the same one. However, I just found a customs declaration from when my dad came back from Europe,dated July 15, 1945,  and it lists a revolver-25 cal. This might mean that this is the gun he brought back from WWII, but ther is no positive way to tell.  It measures 4.5 inches long. One guy I spoke to thought it would be worth as much as $400, and as little as $100. So, I split the difference at $250.  Let me know if you have any questions. I would like to sell this locally if possible.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Egyptian RASHEED semi-auto carbine - only 8000 ever made!!
postcontent:
For sale is an original Egyptian Rasheed (Rashid) carbine in 7.62 x39 caliber. The Rasheed is among the rarest of all military production rifles with only about 8000 ever produced. I won't go into great historical detail because I believe that most who would purchase this rifle will be well aware of it's history and rarity. The rifle is gas operated and has a 10 round magazine that can be quickly reloaded using a standard 7.62 x 39 (10) round stripper clip.

This particular rifle is just about as good a one as you are ever likely to find with regard to physical and mechanical condition. The majority of these rifles are pretty beat up from the service they saw in Egypt. This one however retains almost all of it's original finishes and the bore, action, magazine & bayonet are in excellent condition. It could also serve as a very formidable self defense weapon with similar rate of fire and power to the very popular SKS rifle.

Rifle comes with it's original attached folding bayonet, magazine and sling. The ammo and stripper clips shown in the pictures are also included.

Price for this highly collectible rifle is $1000.00. You'll need to be at least 21 and a Florida resident to purchase.
